Music 438 - Assignment #4\
\
A.\'ca Make a keyboard "instrument" that accompanies any note you play with a\
chord.\'ca \
\
\'95\'c0\uc0\u189  The chord should NOT be a random collection of notes.\'ca Rather, it should\
have a defined structure expressed either as specific pitches, pitch classes, or\
intervallic relationships.\'ca \
\
\'95\'c0\uc0\u189  Each chord or chord structure should be specifically associated with either\
a particular pitch class or classes (e.g., you might decide that chord/structure\
#1 will be triggered anytime you play a C or an F# on the keyboard, regardless\
of register; structure #2 anytime you play a C#; etc.) OR, less flexibly, with a\
specific pitch or pitches (i.e., MIDI note number[s]). \
\
\'95\'c0\uc0\u189 There should be AT LEAST 4 different chord structures in all.\
\
In order to save/manage your chords/structures, I suggest using the \'95\'c0\uc0\u189  coll \'95\'c0\u189 \
object.\'ca (Another, somewhat more cumbersome alternative might be to use multiple\
message boxes.) In order for the chords to be played as blocks, you will need\
the \'95\'c0\uc0\u189  iter \'95\'c0\u189  object.\'ca If you intend to work with pitch classes (as opposed\
to specific note numbers or intervallic structures), you will need the modulo\
operator (\'95\'c0\uc0\u189  % \'95\'c0\u189 ), with 12 as its argument.\
\
\
